name: Keller Rinaudo
text: 17) Under regulation is super visible, while over regulation is invisible

name: Keller Rinaudo
text: 16)Will run the numbers tomorrow

name: Keller Rinaudo
text: 15) compare to the thousands of lifetimes people have lost collectively on slow planes that they would have saved on supersonic ones?

name: Keller Rinaudo
text: 14)But is it worth it in the long run? For example, how many people have been saved by increased airplane safety since 1960? How does this..

name: Keller Rinaudo
text: 13)Regulation saves lives over the short term in very public and obvious ways. Flight got safer after FAA was created.

name: Keller Rinaudo
text: 12)Again, that's $74m for a passenger plane in 1935 and $32b for one in 2007. This is cost of regulation and lack of startups in aviation

name: Keller Rinaudo
text: 11)Unsurprisingly, Dreamliner was plagued with electrical problems. @elonmusk famously offered to help. More info://t.co/0Y8F8AbYwq

name: Keller Rinaudo
text: 10)Result: Boeing spent $32bn developing Dreamliner, their most recent plane. Project was insanely complicated rats nest of subcontractors

name: Keller Rinaudo
text: 9)In 1958, the FAA was created, and the cost of building and testing new airplanes went up a lot. Became impossible for startups to compete

name: Keller Rinaudo
text: 8)Then refunded $3m to gov bc they were under budget, and delivered several extra planes they expected to crash during testing but didn't

name: Keller Rinaudo
text: 7)Tiny team of engineers at Skunkworks took $20m contract to build 20 planes. They designed, tested and delivered first plane in 9 months

name: Keller Rinaudo
text: 6)Favorite example: U2. Designed in 1954. CIA needed plane to fly 50% higher than any built before, in one year. Most thought impossible

name: Keller Rinaudo
text: 5)DC-3 was 1 of the first modern passenger planes, designed by small team of engineers in 2 years. Dev cost of $73.7m (inflation adjusted)

name: Keller Rinaudo
text: 4) I build airplanes, and we see similar trade offs. It used to be possible for startup ups to design and build great airplanes.

name: Keller Rinaudo
text: 3)We trade long term transformational technology breakthroughs for short term safety. Tough for public to weigh these trade offs.

name: Keller Rinaudo
text: 2)How much closer would we be to true life extension (huge impact on human progress) if it didn't cost $3bn to certify a new drug in the US?

name: Keller Rinaudo
text: 1)When regulator misses Thalidomide, public panics, heads roll. But who is mourning loss of billions of yrs of life due to slow research?

text: Inspired by a convo with @balajis to talk about regulation. Thesis: under regulation is super visible, while over regulation is invisible
